      <body>
         <lg type="poem.sonnet-shakespearean" part="N" org="uniform" sample="complete">
            <head>Sonnet 130</head>
            <lg type="quatrain" n="1" part="N" org="uniform" sample="complete">
               <l n="1" part="N">My Mistres eyes are nothing like the Sunne,</l>
               <l n="2" part="N">Currall is farre more red, then her lips red</l>
               <l n="3" part="N">If snow be white, why then her brests are dun:</l>
               <l n="4" part="N">If haires be wiers, black wiers grown on her head:</l>
            </lg>
            <lg type="quatrain" n="2" part="N" org="uniform" sample="complete">
               <l n="5" part="N">I have seene Roses damaskt, red and white,</l>
               <l n="6" part="N">But no such Roses see I in her cheekes,</l>
               <l n="7" part="N">And in some perfumes is there more delight,</l>
               <l n="8" part="N">Then in the breath that from my Mistres reekes.</l>
            </lg>
            <lg type="quatrain" n="3" part="N" org="uniform" sample="complete">
               <l n="9" part="N">I love to heare her speake, yet well I know,</l>
               <l n="10" part="N">That Musicke hath a farre more pleasing sound:</l>
               <l n="11" part="N">I graunt I never saw a goddesse goe,</l>
               <l n="12" part="N">My Mistres when shee walkes treads on the ground.</l>
            </lg>
            <lg type="couplet" n="4" part="N" org="uniform" sample="complete">
               <l n="13" part="N">And yet by heaven I think my love as rare,</l>
               <l n="14" part="N">As any she beli'd with false compare.</l>
            </lg>
         </lg>
